    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n9487" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">φόρμιγξ</span></b> , <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ιγγος</span>: <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">phorminx</span>, a kind of
            <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">lute</span> or <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">lyre.</span> The crosspiece (bridge)
          was called <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ζυγόν</span>, the pegs <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">κόλλοπες</span>. Played not only by the professional
          bard, and by Apollo, <i><span class="en">Il. 24.63</span></i>, but
          exceptionally also by heroes, <i><span class="en">Il.
            9.186</span></i>. In form substantially like the <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">κίθαρις</span> represented in the cut. 
        </div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
